<paragraph id="8BB2354AFFDFFFC972A8FE93FC2CE7A9" blockId="12.[151,1127,327,797]" pageId="12" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis id="B979E958FFDFFFC972A8FE93FE6DE449" bold="true" box="[151,401,327,351]" pageId="12" pageNumber="61">Diagnostic characters.</emphasis>
Elongate, ant-mimetic species. Shiny dorsally, with sparse long hairs. Head long; portion before eyes curved downward; eyes rounded, projecting, well separated from anterior margin of pronotum; antennae slender and long; segment II slightly widened toward its apex. Pronotum subtriangular, smooth; pronotal collar wide; anterior margin narrower than base of head; lateral and basal margins straight; posterior lobe with some strong punctures; both lobes separated by a row of punctures; scutellum slightly elevated. Hemelytra with lateral sides sinuated and with strong punctures as in pronotum; cuneal fracture long, reaching corial-claval suture. Legs slender and very long; unarmed; pseudo-pads at apex on fore and mid tibiae consisting of short membranous prominence bearing long hairs. Abdomen very constricted basally. Uradenia typical. Dorsal half of metapleura smooth; ostiolar peritreme (
<figureCitation id="133629CFFFDFFFC97335FD53FEABE789" box="[266,343,647,671]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="11.[113,152,1513,1532]" captionTargetBox="[137,1064,498,1493]" captionTargetId="figure-77@11.[137,1064,497,1493]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figs. 22–27.22 – Nidicola mitra Drake &amp; Herring, 1964, ostiolar peritreme; 23 – Opisthypselus punctaticollis Reuter, 1909, ostiolar peritreme; 24, 25 – Zopherocoris armatus Reuter, 1871; 24 – fore femora; 25 – ostiolar peritreme; 26, 27 – Scolopella brasiliensis Carayon, 1954; 26 – ostiolar peritreme; 27 – detail of evaporatorium." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5330427" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5330427/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="61">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
), placed basally in metapleura, short, wide, straight, inclined backward and rounded apically; median sulcus reaching only the basal quarter of peritreme.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
